The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether the country's name should be changed to 'Republic of North Macedonia'. This measure would settle a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked Macedonia's requests to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbour means that this claim is made on the Greek territory. Therefore, Greece has vetoed the inclusion of Macedonia in NATO and the EU.
The two governments concluded an agreement in June on the basis of the proposed new name. Nationalist opponents, however, argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum. A boycott campaign casts doubt on the fact that turnout reaches the 50 percent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was: 'Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU by adopting the agreement with Greece?'
Supporters of the name change, which includes Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, inclusion in organisations such as the EU and NATO is worth the price.
"I have come today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, as it means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the result of the vote is not legally binding, enough Members of Parliament have said that they would stick to the result so that it is crucial.
The name change would require a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission said that there had been no reports of irregularities by 1 p.m.
Voter turnout, however, was only 16 percent compared to 34 percent in the last general election in 2016, in which 66 percent of registered voters had cast their votes.
