Macedonia's Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko are giving their vote in the referendum on 30 September 2018 in Strumica, Macedonia on the change of the country's name, which would open Macedonia's way to joining NATO and the European Union.
In front of the parliament in Skopje Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and presented chairs in front of tents set up by people who wanted to boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join raised heads, not through the back entrance," said Kavadarkov.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to take us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of the integration between Europe and Asia."
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will result in much-needed investments for Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I believe that a large majority will be in favour, as more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev after his vote.
He said that a 'yes' result would be a 'confirmation of our future'.
