"The sea belongs to us": land-locked Bolivia hopes that a court will open its way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol in front of the naval headquarters in La Paz, adorned with dewwork.
There's a sea-blue flag blowing on public buildings.
Fleet bases from Titicacasee to Amazon bear the motto: “The sea is our rightful property.
Winning it back is a duty."
Throughout land-locked Bolivia, the memory of the stretch of coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the desire to cross the Pacific again.
These hopes may not be as strong as they have been for decades, as Bolivia is waiting for a ruling from the International Court of Justice to be delivered on 1 October after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and naturally expects the result with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Throughout the country, many Bolivians will follow the ICJ's verdict on large screens, hoping that the court in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia's demand. According to this, Chile is obliged to negotiate over a sovereign access of Bolivia to the sea after decades of sporadic talks.
For Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who is facing a controversial fight for his re-election next year, there is also a lot at stake in the verdict on Monday.
"We are on the verge of returning to the Pacific," he praised at the end of August.
However, some analysts consider it unlikely that the court will decide in favor of Bolivia, and believe that this would also change little.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, is not authorised to assign Chilean territory and has specified that it will not decide on the outcome of any talks.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law, the fact that the judgment of the ICJ is already available six months after the final plea suggests that the case was "not complicated".
Far from supporting Bolivia’s case, the last four years could also be a setback.
"The current Bolivian government has seized on the issue of access to the sea," said Zárate.
She indicated that Morales' warlike rhetoric has suffocated any remaining good will of Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will eventually continue their talks, but after these events this will be extremely difficult.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the view that the court's decision had fallen unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to herald a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to put an end to "the 139-year-long disputes for mutual benefit," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America's most popular presidents – used the theme of the sea as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific," he added.
"The judgment is an opportunity to see that we must overcome the past."
