"However, we do not see any response from the US," he said.
"Without trust in the US, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will by no means disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
While Ri trusted North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phase-wise" approach to denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a incumbent U.S. President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had pledged to work towards "the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the Korean War, which was waged between 1950 and 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first abandon his nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes calls for a easing of the strict international sanctions against North Korea.
'The US insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases the pressure of sanctions to achieve its objective through coercion, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war', said Ri.
“The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a figment of the people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not respond to plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
