Harvard students learn enough to sleep in a course
A new course at Harvard University will ensure that all primary school students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the growing macho culture of keeping up with caffeine and learning all night long.
A scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unneeded when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked me, ‘Why do I find out about this only now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year's first course explained to the students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Managing Director of the University's Health Services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section the students see the image of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They receive information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as the effects of lack of sleep on the sporting performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a "night shift" is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep shortages a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain can be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. He had taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before taking up their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler, students should set an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that comes from electronic screens and LED lighting and can bring the circadian rhythm out of sync, leading to problems when they fall asleep.
