However, he was killed four days later by a sniper and never learned that he had won the highest British war award.
His two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire on Sunday.
One of the grandchildren, Michael Vann, said that this act was full of symbolism, as the memorial stone was unveiled exactly 100 years after the heroic act for which his grandfather was awarded.
According to The London Gazette, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion over the Canal de Saint-Quentin on 29 September 1918; through dense fog and under fierce fire from field cannons and machine guns.
Later, he advanced to the fire line and led the line forward with the "greatest bravery" before rushing forward with a single-handed field weapon and shutting down three of the military units.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was shot by a German sniper on October 4, 1918; slightly more than a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were something he could never do justice to, and at the same time something that makes you humble.
Together with his brother Dr. James Vann, he laid down a wreath after the parade under the direction of the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
