National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In an estate in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape in food search.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insight into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will trace dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown long ear and water bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
A sound analysis of all recordings by experts determines the frequency of bat calls and determines which species does what.
A map and a report of the habitat are then drawn up to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for the bats and how these are used by each species.
This data will help to determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and to show how forest areas can be preserved for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom as a whole have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as flycatchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS responsible for the care of over 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across Scotland takes the theme of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Well administrator David Thompson explains that the estate is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threeave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we don't yet know about bats, so here and on other goods we do these work that will help us to learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of initially excluding the presence of bats before maintenance in the goods, as it was possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and juveniles and wipe out the entire population on the ground.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and in many of our species we don't know what their populations are like."
